                                <p> By Gideon Long</p>
                                <p> LONDON, Sept 23 (Reuters) - Police said on Monday they were  investigating a complaint against the head of the Roman Catholic  Church in England and Wales, Cardinal Cormac Murphy-O'Connor,  under fire for allegedly turning a blind eye to a paedophile  priest.</p>
                                <p> "We received a letter from a man some months ago and we are  looking into the allegations made in it," said a spokesman for  the police in Sussex, southern England.</p>
                                <p> "It had information in it concerning him (Murphy-O'Connor),"  the spokesman told Reuters, without giving further details.</p>
                                <p> The BBC said earlier Murphy-O'Connor, leader of some four  million Catholics, had ignored cases of child abuse committed by  a priest in his diocese in the 1980s.</p>
                                <p> At the time, the cardinal was Bishop of Brighton and Arundel  in Sussex. The priest, father Michael Hill, was later jailed for  abusing nine boys over a 20-year period.</p>
                                <p> The Church said it had not been approached by police and hit  out at the BBC, which broadcast its report on its flagship radio  news programme Today.</p>
                                <p> "Before the appearance of media reports this weekend,  Cardinal Cormac Murphy-O'Connor had no knowledge of any formal  enquiry concerning Michael Hill's moves 20 years ago within the  diocese of Arundel and Brighton," the cardinal's office said in  a statement.</p>
                                <p> "This enquiry is apparently in response to complaints made  by a particular individual. The police have never contacted the  Cardinal in this or any other connection.</p>
                                <p> "The Cardinal is dismayed by the approach of the Today  programme, which broadcast a package that was both unbalanced  and out of all proportion, to news that the police are engaged  in an enquiry."</p>
                                <p> Sussex police said they had sought advice from the Crown  Prosecution Service, which would have a say in any eventual  decision to charge Murphy-O'Connor.</p>
                                <p> They also said they had asked the BBC for details of  documents related to its report. The broadcaster said it had  agreed to cooperate.</p>
                                <p> In its report, the BBC quoted what it said were victims of  the priest and their parents. It did not give their names.</p>
                                <p> The BBC also quoted a woman who said Hill abused her  children.</p>
                                <p> Murphy-O'Connor has admitted making a mistake in allowing  Hill to carry on working as a priest but says his decision was  understandable given the details available to him at the time.</p>
                                <p> The latest allegations will come as a further embarrassment  to the Catholic Church worldwide, which has been rocked by a  series of high-profile sex scandals recently.</p>
                                <p> Revelations of abuse by priests in the United States caused  a nationwide scandal earlier this year and prompted Pope John  Paul to say the Church had to be more careful not to let men  with deviant desires enter the priesthood.    </p>
